## Why Garden?

God placed Adam in the Garden of Eden "to dress it and to keep it" (Genesis 2:15). Before the Fall, before cities, before civilization, humanity's first vocation was a gardener's vocation. This is not accidental. Gardening cultivates virtues that mirror the character of a good person: patience, attentiveness, humility before forces larger than ourselves, and the discipline to plan for a harvest that may be months away.

Practically, a well-kept garden produces fresh food of superior nutritional quality to anything purchased at a grocery store, beautifies a home and neighborhood, supports local pollinators and wildlife, and provides meaningful physical work that connects body, mind, and soul to the natural world.

## Soil: The Foundation of the Garden

Healthy soil is the single most important factor in successful gardening. Plants do not grow in dirt — they grow in a living ecosystem of minerals, organic matter, water, air, and billions of microorganisms.

### Soil Composition

Ideal garden soil is a **loam**: roughly 40% sand, 40% silt, and 20% clay, with 5–10% organic matter. This combination provides:
- **Sand** — drainage and aeration
- **Silt** — water and nutrient retention, workability
- **Clay** — mineral nutrients, structure
- **Organic matter** — microbial life, fertility, moisture retention

### Soil pH

Soil **pH** measures acidity or alkalinity on a scale of 0–14. Most vegetables prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil: **pH 6.0–7.0**.

- Below 6.0 (acidic) — nutrients like phosphorus and calcium become unavailable; blueberries and azaleas thrive.
- Above 7.0 (alkaline) — iron and manganese become less available; may cause yellowing in leaves (chlorosis).

**Lime** (calcium carbonate) raises pH; **sulfur** lowers it. A simple soil test, available at most garden centers or through your local agricultural extension office, tells you where your soil stands. [1]

### Compost: Black Gold

**Compost** is decomposed organic matter — kitchen scraps (no meat), leaves, grass clippings, and garden waste — transformed by microbes and worms into a dark, crumbly, nutrient-rich amendment. Regular addition of compost:
- Improves drainage in clay soils
- Improves water retention in sandy soils
- Feeds beneficial microbes
- Slowly releases nutrients

A simple compost pile — layered "greens" (nitrogen-rich: food scraps, grass) and "browns" (carbon-rich: leaves, cardboard) kept moist and turned occasionally — will produce finished compost in 2–6 months.

## Plant Biology Basics

Understanding how plants grow helps gardeners make better decisions.

### Photosynthesis

Plants convert sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide into sugar (glucose) and oxygen:

$$6\text{CO}_2 + 6\text{H}_2\text{O} + \text{light energy} \rightarrow \text{C}_6\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_6 + 6\text{O}_2$$

This means most vegetables need **full sun** (6–8 hours of direct sunlight daily). Leafy greens and some herbs tolerate partial shade (4–6 hours). Root vegetables need adequate sunlight to produce the carbohydrates stored in their roots.

### Plant Nutrients

Plants require **macronutrients** — nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) — in large quantities, plus secondary macronutrients (calcium, magnesium, sulfur) and micronutrients (iron, zinc, manganese, etc.).

Fertilizer labels show **N-P-K ratios**:
- **Nitrogen (N)** — promotes leafy, vegetative growth
- **Phosphorus (P)** — promotes root development, flowering, and fruiting
- **Potassium (K)** — promotes overall vigor, disease resistance, and fruit quality

A balanced fertilizer (10-10-10) suits general use; a high-phosphorus fertilizer (5-10-5) benefits transplants and flowering plants.

## Planning the Garden

### Site Selection

Choose a garden site that receives full sun, has reasonable access to water, and has relatively good soil (or can be improved). Avoid areas where water pools after rain (poor drainage drowns roots), directly under large trees (root competition and shade), or downhill from areas treated with herbicides.

### Raised Beds vs. In-Ground Beds

| Feature | Raised Beds | In-Ground Beds |
|---------|-------------|----------------|
| Soil control | Excellent — fill with custom mix | Limited by existing soil |
| Drainage | Superior | Depends on site |
| Cost | Higher initial investment | Lower startup cost |
| Weed pressure | Lower | Higher |
| Accessibility | Easier on knees and back | Standard |
| Root depth | Limited by bed depth | Unlimited |

Raised beds (typically 4 ft. wide × 8 ft. long × 12 in. deep) are ideal for beginners: fill them with a blend of topsoil, compost, and coarse sand for an immediately productive growing medium.

### Crop Rotation

Planting the same crop family in the same location year after year depletes specific nutrients and builds up pests and diseases specific to that family. **Rotate** crops by family on a 3–4 year cycle:

1. **Solanums** (tomatoes, peppers, eggplant)
2. **Brassicas** (cabbage, broccoli, kale)
3. **Legumes** (beans, peas) — fix atmospheric nitrogen
4. **Root vegetables** (carrots, beets, potatoes)

### Companion Planting

Certain plants benefit each other when grown in proximity. The classic example is the **Three Sisters** of Native American agriculture: corn (structural support), beans (nitrogen fixation), and squash (ground cover suppressing weeds and retaining moisture) planted together in a mutually beneficial system.

Other classic companions:
- **Basil and tomatoes** — basil may repel aphids and improve tomato flavor
- **Marigolds** — deter nematodes and aphids throughout the garden
- **Nasturtiums** — attract aphids away from more valuable plants (trap crop)

